I often come upon code that restricted the scope of the using statement as a stylistic choice rather than by necessity. It would be consistent to offer "IDE0063 'using' statement can be simplified" here too.

```cs
class C
{
    bool M()
    {
        using (var foo = new MemoryStream())
        {
            // ...
        }

        return true; // Or any compile-time constant or variable read or throw statement
    }
}
```

Should be treated as though it was identical to the return statement first being moved into the using statement, offering:

```cs
class C
{
    bool M()
    {
        using var foo = new MemoryStream();

        // ...

        return true;
    }
}
```

